            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-277-person1529">
                  MARY 
                  HARRIS
               <interp inst="t18280410-277-person1529" type="surname" value="HARRIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-277-person1529" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-277-person1529" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Henry Harris. We live in Augusta-street, Hampstead-road. On the 22d of March, I met the prisoner coming over Blackfriars' - bridge; she was quite a stranger - she nearly stopped me, by seeming to pick up something under my feet; which appeared to be two seals, a ring, and a chain. She stopped me, and said, I should have half; we walked on till we came to the second street over the bridge - she asked me if I knew where there was a silversmiths, I said, No; we walked on till we met a young man - she asked him if he knew where there was a silversmiths; he said, he worked at one - we walked on, and I asked how far she was going to take me - she then asked him the value of them; he said 30l., but we should not get more than 28l. if we went to sell them; she then told me, if I would go with her into the country, she would give me the half part of it - I said I could not; she then told me to give her my ring, and what money I had, and wait at the end of Fleet-market, and she would come to me in an hour and a half, and bring me 12l. I gave her my ring and 4s. 6d., and waited for her till three or four o'clock, but she did not come - I met her again on the following Monday, near the bridge; she crossed the road when she saw me - I crossed after her, and asked her for my ring and my money; she said she did not know what I meant - but I insisted upon having them, or I would raise the street; she had another young man with her then - she said if I would not make a noise, I should have them; we walked on till we met the young man whom I had seen the first time. I asked her again for my property, and she said if I would hold my tongue, I should have them in a few minutes; and the two young men went for it, but they did not return - I waited twenty minutes or half an hour; then called assistance, and gave her into custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-277-person1530">
                  THOMAS 
                  SNUGGS SHARPE
               <interp inst="t18280410-277-person1530" type="surname" value="SNUGGS SHARPE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-277-person1530" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-277-person1530" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I received charge of the prisoner on the 24th; she said if I<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182804100122"></xptr>would let her go the money and ring would be brought to the watch-house; I said that would not do for me, I must lock her up; a woman came to see her; I inquired what she wanted - she very much wished to see her alone; I said I suspected she was a party to the felony, and I must lock her up; she then handed me this ring, this half-crown, a shilling, and some halfpence, and wanted me to let the prisoner go, but I detained them both. The prisoner gave her name as Burke at the watch-house; I ascertained that the ring had been pawned at a shop in Shoe-lane: I went there, and the pawnbroker described the prisoner's person - he knew her by the name of Clifford; she represented herself as a widow.</p>
               <p>The prisoner pleaded distress.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280410-277-verdict1490" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280410-277-verdict1490" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 24.</p>
